# Katelyn Bourgoin - LinkedIn Posts

## Post 1 - [1/6/2026]
[How did my beloved em dash become so damned divisive? The AI-writing pushback is very… human. 

In 2025 the em dash (aka this humble punctuation mark "—") became the smoking gun that "proves" someone used AI to write their LinkedIn post.

Now writers have been using em dashes for centuries. 

Dickens. 
Shakespeare. 
Morrison. 

They all love a good em dash. 

Em dashes are especially popular in online writing. I've been creating content consistently since 2019, and I bet 50% of my posts and newsletters include an em dash. 

(Sometimes I get a little too excited and throw those bad boys around like confetti.) 

But nobody gave a damn about em dashes until we started obsessing over "AI tells".

Now suddenly, they're everywhere… and they make people MAD.  

—
So the real question:

Why does spotting an em dash—and assuming it's AI—make people so bloody angry?

I have 3 theories, backed by behavioral science:

1. Labor Illusion

We place higher value on things we believe required human effort. 

When you spot what you think is an AI "tell," you feel tricked. Content that seemed thoughtful now feels cheap.

2. Authenticity Violation

We expect LinkedIn posts to be a window into someone's mind and experience. 

Thinking a post is AI-generated triggers a sense of betrayal, as if we were duped into believing something fake was real.

3. Effort Justification & Cognitive Dissonance 

If you've just spent hours crafting your own post, someone using AI shortcuts feels deeply unfair. To resolve that psychological discomfort ("Why did I even bother?"), we lash out at the perceived 'cheater'.

So yeah, when you think about it this way... the em dash rage makes perfect psychological sense.

—
I believe that all this em dash backlash is really something much deeper—we're afraid that authentic human expression is becoming extinct, and we're desperately trying to maintain control. 

But authenticity is about so much more than your writing process.

It's determined by whether your ideas resonate, whether your perspective adds value, and whether your unique voice comes through.

So let's stop policing punctuation and start celebrating good ideas—regardless of how they were crafted.

Agreed?

